[size=6][b]Copy Station Logistic Config[/b][/size]

Copies one player station's full logistic configuration onto another in a single right-click. For every ware the source handles, the target station inherits the same storage allocation, buy/sell offers, prices, trade rules and (optionally) the drone-pool configuration.

[size=4][b]Why[/b][/size]

Tuning a single station's logistics by hand is grim. A medium production station typically touches [b]10–20 wares[/b], and each ware has up to [b]9 independently configurable settings[/b]:

[list]
[*]Manual storage allocation (m³)
[*]Automatic-allocation toggle
[*]Buy offer on/off
[*]Buy amount (manual)
[*]Buy price (manual)
[*]Sell offer on/off
[*]Sell amount (manual)
[*]Sell price (manual)
[*]Per-ware trade-rule overrides (buy + sell)
[/list]

A fully tuned station is easily [b]150–400 clicks[/b] to configure from scratch, and three of every nine settings are numbers you must remember exactly. If you want a second station configured identically, the vanilla UI gives you nothing — you alt-tab to a notepad, scribble values, switch back, open the source, forget a number, switch back to read it, switch again, lose your place... I have done this. You probably have too. It is the worst part of running a station empire.

This mod skips all of that. Configure one station the way you want it. Right-click it, pick [b]Set as Logistic Copy Source[/b]. Right-click each target station, pick [b]Apply Logistic Config from &lt;X&gt;[/b], untick the wares you don't want copied (or keep the default "all"), confirm. Done.

[size=4][b]Requirements[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]SirNukes Mod Support APIs[/b] ([url=https://www.nexusmods.com/x4foundations/mods/503]link[/url]). This is a hard dependency; it provides the Lua loader, interact-menu API, and simple menu/options helpers.[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]How to use[/b][/size]

The mod adds three actions to the right-click menu on player-owned stations (visible only on stations, never on build-storage).

[list=1]
[*][b]Set as Logistic Copy Source[/b] — appears on every player station. Marks that station as the source. A notification confirms the selection.
[*][b]Apply Logistic Config from &lt;SourceName&gt;[/b] — appears on every player station [i]except[/i] the source, once a source is set. Opens a picker:
[list]
[*]One checkbox per ware the source handles, defaulting to all selected.
[*][b]All wares[/b] master toggle at the top.
[*][b]Copy drone config[/b] checkbox (off by default; see below).
[*][b]Select / deselect all wares[/b] — flips every ware checkbox.
[*][b]Select only target station wares[/b] — narrows selection to wares the target itself handles, useful when you don't want to push new tradewares onto the target.
[*][b]Confirm[/b] runs the copy. [b]Cancel[/b] closes the picker.
[/list]
[*][b]Clear Logistic Copy Source[/b] — appears once a source is set, on any station. Drops the source so it doesn't linger.
[/list]

The source persists across map opens and saves; a [b]game-load wipes it[/b], since the component reference could be stale and a half-finished copy shouldn't survive a session boundary.

[size=4][b]What gets copied[/b][/size]

Per ware (for every ware the source handles [b]and[/b] the target has storage for — wares the target can't physically hold are silently skipped):

[list]
[*][b]Storage allocation override[/b] (manual m³, or "automatic" if the source is on auto). If the target's remaining storage can't fit the source's allocation, the override is written as 0 and the player is expected to adjust manually once storage modules finish building.
[*][b]Buy offer existence + amount + price[/b] (with their auto/manual toggles).
[*][b]Sell offer existence + amount + price[/b] (with their auto/manual toggles).
[*][b]Per-ware trade-rule overrides[/b] (both buy and sell).
[*]For wares the target doesn't already render in its Logical Station Overview, the ware is registered as a tradeware so the UI exposes it.
[/list]

When [b]Copy drone config[/b] is checked, the station's shared drone pool also gets copied:

[list]
[*]For each drone unit type (transport, defence, repair), the source's manual/auto mode and per-macro target counts are mirrored.
[*]The shared pool capacity is respected — already-built drones on the target are never destroyed; the inbound order delta is the only thing that gets adjusted.
[*]The station-wide "Trade Rule for Supplies" (the single rule that governs both drones and missile resupply) is also copied.
[/list]

Target-side per-macro overrides for drones the source doesn't have are left intact (the player's existing orders survive).

[size=4][b]What does NOT get copied[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]Non-drone supply overrides.
[*]Anything outside the Logical Station Overview (e.g. construction plans, module loadouts).
[/list]

[size=4][b]Cross-station compatibility notes[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]The source and target don't need to be the same module layout. The copy is per-ware, capacity-clamped per transport type.
[*]Copying onto an under-construction station works for any ware the planned modules will eventually accept. Wares not in the plan are skipped.
[*]If the source has a ware the target physically can't hold (no storage of the right transport type), that ware's override is written as 0.
[/list]

[size=4][b]Tips[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Use "Select only target station wares"[/b] when applying onto a station with a much narrower production scope than the source. Avoids pushing irrelevant tradewares onto the target. Unless you want to copy config to a new similar station that is still in construction.
[*]The Apply action does [b]not[/b] wipe the target's existing settings — it only overwrites the wares you selected. Wares you unchecked retain their current target-side configuration.
[*]The source remains set after Apply, so you can copy onto several stations in succession without re-marking the source each time.
[/list]

[size=4][b]Caveats[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]No undo.[/b] Pick carefully; or re-apply with corrected settings.
[*][b]Debug logging is off by default.[/b] Enable it from Extension Options if you need troubleshooting output. This enables both the MD-side [font=Courier New]debug_to_file[/font] logs (file: [font=Courier New]VAS_CopyStationLogistic/copy_station_logistic.txt[/font]) and the Lua [font=Courier New]DebugError[/font] blocks in the in-game debug log window.
[/list]

[size=4][b]Credits[/b][/size]

[list]
